{
  "card_id": "strong_weak_pivots",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Strong and Weak Swing Pivots",
  "aliases": [
    "Strong High",
    "Strong Low",
    "Weak High",
    "Weak Low",
    "Strong/Weak Pivot Labels",
    "trailing extreme labels"
  ],
  "school": "SMC",
  "definition": "A four-label classification (Strong High / Weak High / Strong Low / Weak Low) applied to the most recent swing extremes based on the current swing-trend bias. The label tells the trader whether a pivot is a key reversal level (Strong) or a likely-to-be-broken continuation level (Weak), encoding both pivot location and prevailing structure in a single token. Used by TradingView SMC indicator and equivalent Smart Money Concepts tooling.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "First determine the active swing-trend bias (bullish / bearish / undefined) from the most recent BOS or CHoCH on the swing structure",
    "When swing trend is BULLISH: label the most recent swing LOW as 'Strong Low' (key support; breaking it confirms a CHoCH / reversal). Label the most recent swing HIGH as 'Weak High' (likely to be broken to continue the trend up)",
    "When swing trend is BEARISH: label the most recent swing HIGH as 'Strong High' (key resistance; breaking it confirms a CHoCH / reversal). Label the most recent swing LOW as 'Weak Low' (likely to be broken to continue down)",
    "Strong High + Weak Low together = confirmed bearish structure (the high holds, the low breaks); inverse for bullish",
    "Labels update only when a new swing pivot forms; they remain valid until the next swing-structure event"
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Strong pivots define invalidation levels — a break of a Strong High (in bear) or Strong Low (in bull) is the structural confirmation of a trend reversal and may serve as the trigger for a counter-trend entry. Weak pivots define continuation targets — they are expected to be swept on the way to deeper liquidity. Place protective stops beyond Strong pivots; expect take-profit zones near or just beyond Weak pivots.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Treating every swing high/low as a Strong pivot regardless of structure — Strong only applies to the pivot on the side opposing the trend",
    "Using Strong/Weak labels from a lower timeframe to override higher-timeframe bias",
    "Holding a long position after a Strong Low is decisively broken (the structure has reversed; the label is no longer Strong)",
    "Confusing 'Strong Low' (a swing pivot label) with 'strong higher-time-frame bias' (a general phrase about HTF confluence)"
  ],
